Autosomal and Y chromosome STR analysis for forensics

Alexandre Gouy

November 22, 2016

Two datasets are analysed in this study. Individuals from different Swiss populations were genotypes for 21 autosomal microsatellite (first dataset) and 22 Y-STR loci (second dataset).

1. Autosomal microsatellite analysis

The dataset consists in 689 indivuduals genotyped for 21 autosomal microsatellite loci. Four subpopulations can be considered (with sample sizes 293, 160, 138 and 98).

Main objectives of this analysis:

  • compute basic diversity estimates
  • test for Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium
  • study population structure
  • characterise patterns of linkage disequilibrium (LD) between loci
# Three R packages must be installed to run this analysis
library("adegenet");library("hierfstat");library("pegas")
datpop<-read.genepop("Autosomes.gen",ncode=3)

Allele frequencies and basic summary statistics

First, we can represent the distribution of allele frequencies per locus, overall populations.

freq<-apply(datpop@tab,2,sum)
nam<-strsplit(names(freq),split="[.]")
loc<-as.factor(unlist(lapply(nam,function(x)x[1])))
alle<-as.numeric(unlist(lapply(nam,function(x)x[2])))

DAT<-data.frame(freq,loc,alle)
DAT<-DAT[order(DAT$alle),]

par(mfrow=c(7,3))
par(mar=c(2,2,2,2))
for(i in unique(DAT$loc)){
  barplot(DAT$freq[DAT$loc==i],names.arg=DAT$alle[DAT$loc==i],main=i)
}

Note that given the distribution of frequencies, some loci (e.g. SE33) do not seem to follow a (Generalised) Stepwise Mutation Model. A combined K-allele/SMM could be more appropriate. However, intermediate alleles appear rare and the distributions are relatively smooth of without them.

Basic diversity estimates

div <- summary(datpop)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
barplot(div$loc.n.all, xlab="Number of alleles", ylab="",horiz=TRUE,las=1)
barplot(div$Hobs, xlab="Observed Heterozygosity", ylab="",horiz=TRUE,las=1)
plot(div$Hobs, div$Hexp, xlab="Observed Heterozygosity", ylab="Expected Heterozygosity")
abline(0,1,lty=2)

Linkage disequilibrium analysis

Linkage disequilibrium between pairs of loci has been tested using Arlequin. A few loci appear significantly associated (8 out of 210 combination tested) at a 5% significance level. However, none of them resist to a Bonferroni correction (new threshold is alpha = 0.05/210 = 0.00024).

Furthermore, the p-values seem to be uniformly distributed (confirmed by the KS test):

Conclusion

A comment on patterns of LD: LD has been tested by pooling all the subpopulations, but population structure can impact the results, even if it appears weak (cf. Fst values). For example, for highly polymorphic loci such as SE33 (He > 0.95), even weak population structure would generate LD if populations are pooled (related to Wahlund effect).

These autosomal microsatellite appear to be compatible with classical microsatellite mutation models. They present a high intra-individual diversity (could be confirmed by running an AMOVA), and the population structure seems really low in Switzerland. They appear appropriate for forensics analysis.

2. Y-chromosome microsatellite analysis

The dataset consists in 481 male indivuduals genotyped for 22 STR loci located on the Y chromosome.

Main objectives of this analysis:

  • compute basic diversity estimates
  • characterise patterns of linkage disequilibrium (LD) between loci
  • study population structure using multivariate analysis
# Three R packages must be installed to run this analysis
library("adegenet");library("hierfstat");library("pegas")

# data preparation
dat<-read.table("Ychrom.txt",header=TRUE,sep="\t",colClasses="character")
rownames(dat)<-dat$ind
dat2<-df2genind(dat[,-1:-2],ncode=2);pop(dat2)<-dat$pop

# information about the samples
samples<-read.table("samples.txt",sep="\t",header=TRUE)
rownames(samples)<-samples$id
SAMP<-samples[dat$ind,]

Allele frequencies and basic summary statistics

First, we can represent the distribution of allele frequencies per locus, overall populations.

freq<-apply(dat2@tab,2,sum)
nam<-strsplit(names(freq),split="[.]")
loc<-as.factor(unlist(lapply(nam,function(x)x[1])))
alle<-as.numeric(unlist(lapply(nam,function(x)x[2])))

DAT<-data.frame(freq,loc,alle)
DAT<-DAT[order(DAT$alle),]

par(mfrow=c(6,4))
par(mar=c(2,2,2,2))
for(i in unique(DAT$loc)){
  barplot(DAT$freq[DAT$loc==i],names.arg=DAT$alle[DAT$loc==i],
          main=i)
}

The distribution of allele frequencies is unimodal most of the time, in agreement with microsatellite mutation models such as SMM/GSM.

A notable exception concerns the two loci DYS438 and DYS392 which present a bimodal distribution. This is the case in most European populations but not in Asia and Africa. The two loci are physically linked and present strong LD patterns.

Although observed patterns could be explained by mutational processes, some authors have shown that patterns of diversity at these two loci are still compatible with a SMM (Gusmão et al., 2003).

Genetic diversity

div <- summary(dat2)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
barplot(div$loc.n.all, xlab="Number of alleles", ylab="",horiz=TRUE,las=1)
barplot(div$Hexp, xlab="Observed Heterozygosity", ylab="",horiz=TRUE,las=1)

Linkage disequilibrium

We compute a measure of linkage disequilibrium between all pairs of loci:

X<-as.loci(dat2)
matLD<-matrix(NA,nrow=22,ncol=22)
rownames(matLD)<-colnames(matLD)<-names(dat2@all.names)
for(i in 1:22){
  for(j in 1:22){
    if(i!=j)matLD[i,j]<-LD(X,locus=c(i,j))$T2[3]
  }
}
matLD<--1*log10(matLD)
diag(matLD)<-NA
matLD[lower.tri(matLD)] <- NA

par(mar=c(5,5,5,5))
col<-rgb(0,0,1,alpha=seq(0,1,0.001))
image(t(matLD),col = col,frame=F,xaxt="n",yaxt="n")
axis(1,at=seq(0,1,length.out=ncol(matLD)),labels=colnames(matLD),las=2)
axis(4,at=seq(0,1,length.out=nrow(matLD)),labels=rownames(matLD),las=2)

This plot represents patterns of LD between pairs of loci. The more blue, the more significant is the LD. Note that almost all pairs of loci are significantly linked on the Y chromosome.

It is worth noticing that, again, DYS392 and DYS438 are outliers. Indeed, LD is really high between them, but also with all other loci.

Multivariate analysis

We can run a PCA (Principal Component Analysis) on our dataset.

library(ade4)
library(rgl)
library(knitr)
knit_hooks$set(webgl = hook_webgl)

FREQ<-makefreq(dat2)
## 
##  Finding allelic frequencies from a genpop object... 
## 
## ...done.
pcaY<-dudi.pca(FREQ, nf = 3, scannf = FALSE)

Then we plot the results, by projecting individuals on axis 1 and 2 (first plot) as well as on axis 1 and 3 (second plot). The groups correspond to the mother tongue: german (d), italian (i) of french (f).

s.class(pcaY$li, fac=as.factor(SAMP$mother.tongue),

        axesel=FALSE, cstar=0, cpoint=2,xax=1,yax=2)

We can also cluster the individuals by regions (groups of cantons):

s.class(pcaY$li, fac=as.factor(SAMP$Group),
        col=transp(funky(12),.6),
        axesel=FALSE, cstar=0, cpoint=2,xax=1,yax=2)

This time, clustered by canton:

cl<-SAMP$Group

You must enable Javascript to view this page properly.

We can also examine the contribution of the different alleles to this PCA:

loadingplot(pcaY$c1^2)

Alleles explaining most of the variance are found in a relatively small number of loci. Furthermore, most of these loci present the strongest patterns of LD (see above). Two alleles per locus explain most of the variance (e.g. DYS438 10 and 12; DYS392 11 and 13), suggesting that two major haplotypes segregate in Switzerland.

This suggests that the structure we observe in these data is likely to be more ancient than the separation of Swiss populations.

Conclusion, perspectives

DYS438 and DYS392 present a bimodal distribution of allele frequencies, but this pattern still reflects demographic history (Gusmão et al., 2003). The results of LD and multivariate analysis suggest that they should have a low mutation rate, and that the differentiation between the two major haplotypes is ancient. These markers are not sufficient to study population structure in Switzerland (haplogroup inference from Y-STR appears to be more informative).

Furthermore, the weak population structure observe in PCA projections can be an atifact. Indeed, it has been shown that uneven sampling has a strong influence on PCA projections (McVean, 2009).

Concerning lower-scale population structure, we observe more genetic differentiation for Y-chromosome loci than for autosomal STRs. However, population structure remains weak. To discriminate between Swiss populations, one would need to get more markers.
